## Need ✅

**KSP** — the entire engine. Scans classpath, finds all Modifier extensions, generates the wrapper functions. This is 80% of the project.

**Gradle Plugin** — wires KSP into the dev's project automatically. Dev adds one line, gets everything. Without this, setup is too manual.

**Runtime library (tiny)** — just declares the `.cw()` string variant and holds any helper types KSP needs to reference in generated code. Maybe 50 lines total.

---

## Do NOT need ❌

**Compiler Plugin (K2/IR)** — you're not transforming syntax or adding new language constructs. KSP generation is enough. K2 plugin adds months of complexity for zero extra benefit at v1.

**IDE Extension** — since you're generating real Kotlin functions, the IDE already understands them natively. Autocomplete, go-to-definition, all work for free because the generated `.kt` files are real Kotlin.

**Annotation Processor (KAPT)** — KSP replaces this entirely. Never use KAPT for new projects.

